In [20]:
def kernel_function(x1, x2, sigma):
    nominator = np.sum((x1 - x2)**2, axis=-1, dtype='float')
    nominator[nominator > 50*sigma**2] = np.inf #cut-off, exp function will be 0
    return np.exp(-1 * nominator / (2 * sigma**2))
In [9]:
def sparse_kernel_matrix(x1, x2, sigma):
    sparse_kernel = scipy.sparse.dok_matrix((x1.shape[0], x2.shape[0])) # sparse matrix
    xi2 = np.arange(x2.shape[0])

    for xi1 in range(x1.shape[0]):
        kappa = kernel_function(x1[xi1], x2, sigma)
        sparse_kernel[xi1, xi2[np.argwhere(kappa!=0)]] = kappa[np.argwhere(kappa!=0)]
    return sparse_kernel.tocsc()
In [10]:
def alpha(x, y, sigma, tau): # computes the weight matrix
    G = sparse_kernel_matrix(x, x, sigma)
    for idx in range(x.shape[0]):
        G[idx, idx] += tau
    return scipy.sparse.linalg.spsolve(G, y)
In [11]:
def replace_0(y_new): # this method replaces zeros in the sparse matrix with y_new elements
    img_reg = image[:,:]
    img_reg[x_0[:,0], x_0[:,1]] = y_new
    return img_reg
In [12]:
def kernel_regression(x_full, x_0, y, sigma, tau):
    alpha_matrix = alpha(x_full, y, sigma, tau)
    kappa_matrix = sparse_kernel_matrix(x_0, x_full, sigma)
    y_new = kappa_matrix @ alpha_matrix
    return replace_0(y_new)

def NW_kernel_regression(x_full, x_0, sigma): # Nadaraya-Watson kernel regression
    kappa_matrix = sparse_kernel_matrix(x_0, x_full, sigma)
    ones_mat = np.ones((y.shape))
    y_new = kappa_matrix @ y / (kappa_matrix @ ones_mat)
    return replace_0(y_new)

image = plt.imread('cc_90.png')

x_sparse = np.mgrid[:image.shape[0], :image.shape[1]].reshape((2, -1)).T # gets coordinates
y_sparse = image[x_sparse[:,0], x_sparse[:,1]]
x_full = x_sparse[y_sparse != 0]
x_0 = x_sparse[y_sparse == 0]
y = y_sparse[y_sparse != 0]

I think the best result is obtained for sigma = 4 and tau = 0.1. Small sigma cannot fill all sparse pixels and as sigma increases small details in the image get lost. As tau increases, image becomes darker. The Nadaraya-Watson kernel regression gave good approximations for low sigma values. As sigma increases image becomes blurrier.
